            "id": "2ca746bd-5c03-4125-b39b-c3b273671244_1101d165-3d55-4a9b-ba29-969d64129437",
            "dom_id": "1101d165-3d55-4a9b-ba29-969d64129437",
            "len": 824,
            "post_value": "At Microsoft, data and analytics have been central to almost everything I've worked on. I built a Power BI dashboard to track operational toil across 140+ teams, which gave leadership visibility into automation gaps and helped prioritize high-impact investments. I also standardized analytics workflows across Azure's resilience program, turning ad-hoc tracking into a platformized system that supported 45+ annual drills and contributed to $14M+ in business impact. Earlier, during my 2022 internship, I helped generate $3M in accelerated revenue by driving alignment on a data-driven prioritization framework used across 140+ teams. Across those projects, I've worked closely with SQL, Power BI, Tableau, and data pipelines, and I've gotten comfortable translating raw data into something stakeholders can actually act on."
          },
          {
            "id": "2ca746bd-5c03-4125-b39b-c3b273671244_846a48fe-30a1-4a28-8db1-9e7b0400a449",
            "dom_id": "846a48fe-30a1-4a28-8db1-9e7b0400a449",
            "len": 773,
            "post_value": "I've used SQL both academically, through coursework in databases and data science at the University of Houston, and in hands-on analytics work. At Microsoft, I used SQL to extract and analyze operational data as part of building out the resilience analytics system and supporting the Power BI dashboards I developed for tracking drill execution and team-level toil. I also worked with semantic search and data pipelines where SQL underpinned how we structured and queried documentation data, helping cut lookup time by 83% after migrating to a governed, AI-powered toolset. My use has primarily been in the analytics and data extraction space, writing queries to surface patterns, join operational datasets, and support decision-making for engineering and leadership teams."
          },
          {
            "id": "2ca746bd-5c03-4125-b39b-c3b273671244_ff9996cd-7df5-45dd-8ab8-4d2c3d678e9a",
            "dom_id": "ff9996cd-7df5-45dd-8ab8-4d2c3d678e9a",
            "len": 1172,
            "post_value": "Yes, a meaningful part of my work at Microsoft has been customer-facing. I served as bridge lead for a sovereign-cloud network isolation test tied to a $1.5B+ enterprise contract, coordinating directly across engineering, sales, and post-sales teams alongside customers like Databricks, Walmart, SAP, and NetApp. I also ran user demos and enablement sessions during my 2023 internship, driving adoption of AI-driven analytics workflows across 14 key teams. Those experiences required translating complex technical work into something customers could understand, trust, and act on.\n\nWhat draws me to customer-facing work is that it keeps you honest. You stop optimizing for internal metrics and start solving real problems. I genuinely enjoy the discovery side, asking the right questions, finding where the pain actually lives, and then building something that addresses it. The feedback loop from customers is also where the best product ideas come from, and I've seen that firsthand when field insights I surfaced shaped roadmap decisions at Microsoft. A role like this one, where technical depth and customer engagement are both required, is exactly where I want to be."
          }
        ],
