          },
          {
            "id": "4eee3e4f-6720-43e8-9596-a30080255de3_f725ef6c-7a56-45b1-918e-68a2875f61d7",
            "dom_id": "f725ef6c-7a56-45b1-918e-68a2875f61d7",
            "len": 1337,
            "post_value": "The product I'm most proud of is the Resilience Automation Platform I built at Microsoft, which I took from 0 to 1 as the PM. The core problem was that Azure's recovery validation process was manual, slow, and didn't scale - we were running drills for customers like Databricks, Walmart, SAP, and NetApp, but execution depended on a small team and tribal knowledge. I defined the self-service scheduling requirements, designed feedback loops that made the system trustworthy over time, and drove cross-functional alignment to ship it. The result was a 30% reduction in operational toil and a platform that could sustain 45+ annual drills without adding headcount.\n\nWhat makes me proud of it isn't just the outcome - it's the kind of problem it was. The value was earned through data quality and customer trust, not just features. I had to partner with data science to build extraction and normalization pipelines that converted raw telemetry into drill intelligence customers could actually act on in real time. I also had to care deeply about explainability and auditability, especially on a sovereign-cloud test tied to a $1.5B+ enterprise contract where every decision had to be traceable. That combination - building a trust-earning data product under high-stakes conditions - is exactly the muscle I want to keep developing at Ramp."
          },
          {
            "id": "4eee3e4f-6720-43e8-9596-a30080255de3_cd793c40-87aa-4776-9b67-e147c1ce1895",
            "dom_id": "cd793c40-87aa-4776-9b67-e147c1ce1895",
            "len": 3,
            "post_value": "No."
          },
          {
            "id": "4eee3e4f-6720-43e8-9596-a30080255de3_77df3174-8e79-4de4-92c5-5cc838d57537",
            "dom_id": "77df3174-8e79-4de4-92c5-5cc838d57537",
            "len": 1474,
            "post_value": "The work I've done at Microsoft maps closely to what this role requires. I built a 0-to-1 data product where trust and accuracy were the core value proposition, partnered with data science to normalize raw telemetry into actionable benchmarks, and designed feedback loops that let customers act on intelligence at exactly the right moment. I also shipped an AI agent that restructured planning workflows, cutting cycle time by 39% and increasing capacity by 21%. The Vendor Intelligence and Marketplace role is asking for the same instincts applied to a different data set - spend and contract data instead of recovery telemetry - and that translation feels natural to me.\n\nWhat draws me to Ramp specifically is the scale and uniqueness of the data asset. Seeing billions in real-world spend across 70,000 companies isn't something a point solution or a procurement startup can replicate - it's a genuine structural advantage, and the price benchmarking and contract intelligence products are the right bet to build on top of it. Most businesses genuinely don't know if they're overpaying, and replacing that guesswork with data-driven decision moments at the exact instant of a renewal or signature is a sharp product thesis. I want to be one of the first PMs building that buyer-side intelligence layer, and I think the combination of my technical background, data product experience, and comfort operating under high auditability requirements makes me well-suited for it."
          }
        ],
