          },
          {
            "id": "cb309e47-96a1-405e-b475-5cefc548cc06_question_7784354101",
            "dom_id": "question_7784354101",
            "len": 1365,
            "post_value": "My work at Microsoft has been fundamentally about turning complex technical capabilities into scalable, repeatable systems that drive real business outcomes. I architected Azure's recovery validation platform from a 2-person operation into a self-service system delivering $14M+ in business impact, and built an AI agent that reduced planning cycle time by 39% while expanding capacity without adding headcount. That pattern - designing architectures that unlock value at scale, then building the frameworks and playbooks to make it repeatable - is exactly what this Solutions Architect role is asking for. I want to bring that same approach to a product domain I find genuinely compelling.Synthesia sits at an intersection I care about: AI that has clear, measurable enterprise utility rather than novelty for its own sake. The fact that over 90% of the Fortune 100 are already using the platform tells me the core value proposition is proven - the challenge now is deepening adoption, building integration ecosystems, and helping customers operationalize it at scale. That is the kind of problem I want to be working on. The backing from investors like Nvidia's NVentures and the trajectory from Series E at a $4B valuation signals serious infrastructure ambition, and I want to help build the technical foundation that gets Synthesia from product to ecosystem."
          },
          {
            "id": "cb309e47-96a1-405e-b475-5cefc548cc06_question_7784355101",
            "dom_id": "question_7784355101",
            "len": 1200,
            "post_value": "Yes. My technical work has consistently involved API-driven systems, workflow automation, and code. At Microsoft, I built an AI agent to automate drill planning workflows using LLM-powered tooling, and I led the delivery of an internal Resilience Automation Platform that exposed self-service scheduling workflows to engineering orgs across Azure - both of which required hands-on work with APIs, YAML-based configuration, and integration design. I also worked on an AI-powered semantic search tool with rigorous metadata standards, and partnered with engineering teams to implement CI/CD pipelines that reduced deployment cycle time by 25%.My computer science background at the University of Houston (GPA 3.8, coursework in algorithms, databases, AI, and machine learning) gave me the foundation to engage at a code level, not just a conceptual one. In practice, I sit comfortably at the boundary between architecture and implementation - I can read and write code, design API integrations, and also translate that technical work into business-facing narratives for VP- and C-level stakeholders. That combination is what I have been doing at Microsoft and what I would bring directly to this role."
          },
          {
            "id": "cb309e47-96a1-405e-b475-5cefc548cc06_question_7784356101",
            "dom_id": "question_7784356101",
            "len": 1266,
            "post_value": "My direct employer experience has been with large enterprises rather than SaaS startups - Microsoft and Amazon Robotics. That said, the work I did within those organizations closely mirrors what startup-facing product utilization work requires. At Microsoft, I drove platform adoption for AI-powered code generation workflows by conducting live demos and enablement sessions that activated 14 key Azure engineering teams, saving 37 engineering hours monthly. I also facilitated 11+ discovery interviews with Azure service teams to surface integration gaps and secure stakeholder buy-in for new platform capabilities - essentially acting as an internal solutions architect for product adoption.On the customer-facing side, the enterprise customers I worked with at Microsoft include Databricks, Walmart, SAP, and NetApp - large accounts where I advised VP- and C-level stakeholders on technical decisions and helped operationalize complex infrastructure. I have not done this work directly for SaaS startups, but the core skills - scoping solutions, building adoption playbooks, connecting use cases to measurable outcomes, and influencing technical and executive stakeholders - are directly transferable, and I am confident in applying them in Synthesia's context."
          },
          {
            "id": "cb309e47-96a1-405e-b475-5cefc548cc06_question_7784357101",
            "dom_id": "question_7784357101",
            "len": 24,
