            "dom_id": "5799ecfb-306a-4208-9ddd-d896005a18e5",
            "len": 33,
            "post_value": "https://linkedin.com/in/cyshekari"
          },
          {
            "id": "3f9147ee-8aea-4ce6-9066-cf7f9dd6ae9c_12e1de5f-49bb-4cd3-9d58-991934ff1bd2",
            "dom_id": "12e1de5f-49bb-4cd3-9d58-991934ff1bd2",
            "len": 0,
            "post_value": ""
          },
          {
            "id": "3f9147ee-8aea-4ce6-9066-cf7f9dd6ae9c_c2b27edc-aa94-4266-b8fc-9df822f563e4",
            "dom_id": "c2b27edc-aa94-4266-b8fc-9df822f563e4",
            "len": 1248,
            "post_value": "My work at Microsoft has centered on building and scaling structured implementation programs, managing cross-org onboarding workflows, and acting as the bridge between engineering teams and external stakeholders under real delivery pressure. The Technical Solutions Engineer role at Talos maps directly onto that: owning end-to-end client onboarding, driving API and connectivity integrations to production, and keeping multiple concurrent implementations on schedule. That combination of technical fluency and structured project execution is where I've built my career, and this role plays to those exact strengths.What draws me specifically to Talos is the seriousness of what they're building. Institutional digital asset infrastructure is genuinely hard to get right - the connectivity surface area alone, spanning exchanges, liquidity providers, OMS and EMS layers, FIX and REST integrations, is a compelling technical problem. Talos is clearly the operator that understands both traditional capital markets and crypto at depth, and the Andreessen Horowitz framing captures it well. I want to work somewhere where the platform actually matters to sophisticated counterparties, and where the implementation work has real stakes. That's Talos."
          },
          {
            "id": "3f9147ee-8aea-4ce6-9066-cf7f9dd6ae9c_5861cbbf-ed2d-496e-9e8e-c558b67e5130",
            "dom_id": "5861cbbf-ed2d-496e-9e8e-c558b67e5130",
            "len": 1931,
            "post_value": "I want to be straightforward: my background is in technical program management at Microsoft and Amazon Robotics, not directly in capital markets. I haven't owned FIX connectivity or exchange onboarding in a trading context. That said, the core mechanics of what this role requires - structured end-to-end implementation, multi-stakeholder integration coordination, and getting complex technical systems to a stable production state - are exactly what I've been doing at scale.\n\nThe closest parallel is the work I led on Azure's resilience validation program. I scaled it from a two-person operation into a platformized system that sustained 45+ annual drills across enterprise clients including Databricks, Walmart, and SAP. Each drill was effectively a high-stakes implementation: I owned the onboarding workflow, coordinated resolution across engineering and external stakeholders, managed milestone tracking, and communicated progress to executives. One specific integration - a sovereign-cloud network isolation drill tied to a $1.5B+ enterprise contract - required me to serve as bridge lead across internal engineering teams and external counterparties, troubleshoot integration blockers in real time, and drive the execution to completion on a fixed timeline. That's the same motion Talos needs for client and liquidity provider onboarding.\n\nI've also built the adjacent technical skills directly - Python scripting, SQL, API-based integrations, configuration management, and CLI environments - and I've been an active member of a Trading Enthusiast Club throughout my time at UH, which is where my interest in market infrastructure and electronic trading developed. I'm coming in knowing I'll need to ramp on capital markets workflows and FIX specifics, and I'm committed to doing that fast. What I bring on day one is the implementation rigor, stakeholder management, and technical fluency to run complex onboardings well."
          }
        ],
        "missing": [],
        "errors": []
      }
