            "len": 1369,
            "post_value": "AI tooling is now a core part of how I work, not an add-on. At Microsoft, I built an internal AI agent for drill planning that restructured how we scheduled and coordinated resilience tests across Azure. That work cut planning cycle time by 39% and increased drill capacity by 21%. I didn't just use a tool off the shelf - I defined the workflow, identified where automation created leverage, and iterated on it based on how engineering teams actually used it.\n\nDuring my 2023 internship at Microsoft, I also led the adoption of AI-driven code generation workflows across 14 Azure service teams, running customer-facing demos and training sessions that saved 37 engineering hours monthly. Separately, I implemented an AI-powered semantic search tool for internal developer documentation that cut lookup time by 83%. Both of those required me to understand the technical underpinnings well enough to explain them clearly and get skeptical engineers to actually change their habits.\n\nDay-to-day, I use AI-assisted development tools to move faster on prototypes, drafts, and analysis work. I treat them the way I'd treat any good tool - useful when applied with judgment, not as a replacement for thinking through the actual problem. The projects I find most interesting are the ones where AI changes the architecture of how work gets done, not just the speed of one task."
