          {
            "id": "9f142921-e45e-449b-8df6-501708d7a1ea_0b43208a-905a-45fb-84b5-154e673a0fe8",
            "dom_id": "0b43208a-905a-45fb-84b5-154e673a0fe8",
            "len": 1245,
            "post_value": "My work at Microsoft has centered on exactly the problem Writer is solving. I built an internal AI agent that integrated LLM-powered automation into end-to-end orchestration workflows, cutting planning cycle time by 39% and expanding drill capacity by 21%. I also championed enterprise adoption of AI-driven code generation, running technical demos and enablement sessions across 14 Azure service teams. That pattern, finding where AI creates real business leverage and then architecting the system and driving adoption, is what this role is asking for at scale with Fortune 500 customers.\n\nWriter's bet on an end-to-end enterprise platform, rather than a point tool bolted onto existing workflows, is the right architectural approach for how large companies actually need to deploy AI. The combination of grounded LLMs, agentic workflows, and a platform that unites IT and business teams is a technically serious product, not just a wrapper. The customer roster, Mars, Marriott, Uber, Vanguard, signals that Writer is winning real enterprise trust, not just pilots. That's the stage of company I want to be building at, where the architecture decisions I make with customers actually shape how large organizations operate with AI going forward."
          },
          {
            "id": "9f142921-e45e-449b-8df6-501708d7a1ea_9776654b-fcbf-46fa-ba45-2183f2d5f5b6",
            "dom_id": "9776654b-fcbf-46fa-ba45-2183f2d5f5b6",
            "len": 1352,
            "post_value": "One example that comes to mind is the resilience automation work I led at Microsoft. I inherited a 2-person manual operation and needed to scale it to something the organization could sustain without me running every execution. That meant rebuilding the system from the ground up, defining product requirements, building self-service scheduling capabilities, and getting cross-functional buy-in from teams that had no formal obligation to participate. The result was a platform that now sustains 45+ annual drills and has driven $14M+ in business impact across Fortune 500 customers like Databricks, Walmart, SAP, and NetApp.\n\nWhat I think that example illustrates is a builder's mindset applied to a messy, real-world enterprise problem. I didn't wait for a cleaner mandate or more resources. I ran discovery with the stakeholders who had the context, translated what I learned into a concrete architecture, and shipped something that outlasted my direct involvement in it. I also built an AI agent on top of that foundation, integrating LLM-powered automation into the drill planning workflow, which reduced the planning cycle by 39%. The two things together, building the platform and then layering AI into it once the foundation was solid, reflect how I think about enterprise transformation: get the architecture right, then accelerate it with AI."
          }
        ],
